Report

Summary:

Our best model, LightGBM, achieves a test PR-AUC of 0.2489 compared to 0.1945 for the baseline decision tree, representing a 33% improvement. Through controlled experiments on learning rate and number of estimators, we provide empirical evidence of the bias-variance trade-off and demonstrate how boosting algorithms navigate this fundamental machine learning challenge.

Key Findings:

  • Boosting methods improve PR-AUC by 20-35% over single decision trees
  • Learning rates between 0.05-0.1 provide optimal bias-variance balance
  • Early stopping prevents overfitting by identifying the optimal iteration count
  • LightGBM provides 1.2X training speedup over XGBoost with comparable accuracy

1. Introduction:

The objective of this assignment is to explore the power of boosting methods like Gradient Boost, Extreme Gradient Boost and Light Gradient Boost.

To complete the assessment, I have used the Home Credit Default Risk Dataset, where I predicted whether an applicant would repay a loan or not. This is a standard supervised classification task and I have used Decision Trees to classify the above.

The dataset used contained 307,511 rows and 122 columns, including numeric features like AMT_CREDIT_TOTAL, AMT_INCOME_TOTAL, AMT_ANNUITY_TOTAL and categorical features like NAME_HOUSING_TYPE, OCCUPATION_TYPE, just to name a few. The target variable (TARGET) represents whether a client defaulted (1) or repaid (0)

The assignment workflow involves:

  • Data cleaning and handling missing values
  • Feature engineering (transformations and encoding)
  • Model Training
  • Model Boosting
  • Evaluation of models using different metrics and visualisation of differences after boosting
  • Interpreting results with a focus on understanding how boosting impacts predictive performance, especially in the case of unbalanced data.

Question.1 Why was this binary classification particularly challenging?

  • Class Imbalance: Defaults are rare events (typically 5-10% of applications)
  • Feature Complexity: Mixed data types (numerical, categorical) with non-linear relationships
  • Business Constraints: False negatives (missing defaults) are more costly than false positives
  • Interpretability Requirements: Lenders need to explain decisions to regulators and customers

Question. 2 Why was Boosting preferred and how does it improve generalization?

Boosting methods improve generalisation by sequentially building a strong model from many weak learners, where each new learner focuses on correcting the errors made by the previous ones. This iterative process reduces bias by giving more weight to difficult-to-classify data points and ultimately creates a robust, highly accurate model.

2. Methods: Preprocessing

2.1 Data Understanding and Preprocessing:

  • Strategy 1: Missing Values were handled by dropping the data with more than 90% missing values because excessive missingness would skew the data and just introduce noise.

  • Strategy 2: Imputing the median for numeric, mode and "MISSING" for the categorical values for better consistency and distribution.

  • For tree-based models (Decision Tree, XGBoost, LightGBM), Label Encoding was applied to binary categorical variables, and Ordinal Encoding to multi-class ones using a ColumnTransformer pipeline. We avoided using OneHotEncoding because some of the categorical variables had 50+ unique values, which would have increased the dataset and made it sparse, losing some of the correlations. This approach avoids data leakage and ensures consistent preprocessing during model training and prediction.

  • To ensure unbiased evaluation, the data was split into 70% training set, 15% validation set and 15% test set. Stratification was also applied to maintain class distribution.

2.2 EDA:

After exploring the dataset using graphs, these were the key findings:

  • The target distribution is highly imbalanced with 90% of no loan defaults and 10% of loan defaults.

  • Most of our numeric columns are highly right-skewed, most of the values lie in the lower end of the scale, and a few lie on the higher end.

  • The most common type of loan is Cash Loans.

Initial results showed high training accuracy but low validation accuracy, indicating overfitting. Training accuracy gave 100% accuracy, which made it clear that the tree needs to be pruned or the learning rate needs to be changed.

Observations:Shallow trees (depth < 6) underfit, while deeper trees overfit. The best trade-off was achieved around max_depth = 8. This can also be shown with learning curves below.

  • Conclusion: A Single decision tree suffers from the bias-variance dilemma. Shallow trees have high bias (underfitting), deep trees have high variance (overfitting).

3.2 Boosting Methods

1. Gradient Boosting

Gradient Boosting builds an additive model in a forward stage-wise manner. In other words, Gradient Boosting sequentially builds trees that correct the residuals of previous trees. We experimented with different values of learning rate, n_estimators to find the best model.

Improvement over Decision Tree:

Test ROC-AUC: +5.11% (0.7211 0.7580)
Test PR-AUC: +23.13% (0.1945 0.2395)

When we analysed the model over multiple learning rates, we observed that smaller values give high bias and larger values add variance, as shown below. The least overfit gap is found in learning rates 0.05-0.1.

Observation: A moderate learning rate (0.050.1) gave the best generalisation, balancing bias and variance.

Question. Use of scale_pos_weight:

This is used to handle imbalanced datasets by giving more importance to the positive class during training. When not added in XGBoost, the Recall was less than 2% representing that it is not able to predict the positive class (minority class), which here was those who defaulted on the loan. And after adding, it increased to 70% but the precision reduced.

Observation:

  • Since we are more interested in PR-AUC, we notice that it is almost the same for both with and without scaling the unbalanced data, without giving a better result because of high precision.

  • XGBoost achieved a testing ROC-AUC of 0.76, outperforming Gradient Boosting and Decision Tree, with significantly faster convergence. The best parameters were n_estimators to be 300, max_depth to be 3-4 and learning rate to be 0.05. This shows that the tree depth is not too shallow or deep, and the learning rate also aligns with our previous observations.

  • I have used Early Stopping as well to prevent overfitting by stopping the training process as soon as a model's validation performance worsens. When tried with n_estimators above 300, the model stopped around 241 because of early stopping.

  • Recall (0.67) is relatively high when we have tried balancing using scale_pos_weight, meaning the model successfully captures most of the actual defaulters an important goal in credit risk applications. Precision (0.168) is low, which means the model also produces more false positives. This trade-off (high recall, low precision) is desirable in high-risk financial contexts, where missing a true defaulter is more costly than flagging a few non-defaulters.

  • The validation and test scores are consistent, showing good generalisation and minimal overfitting.

4. Evaluation Metrics and Visualisation:

4.1 Learning Rate Sensitivity Analysis

I conducted controlled experiments to isolate the effect of learning rate on model performance and the bias-variance trade-off. All hyperparameters were fixed at optimal values from tuning, and the learning rate was iterated over to see the patterns and best trends.

Key Observations in Gradient Boosting:

learning_rate train_roc_auc val_roc_auc gap_roc
0.01 0.7241 0.7208 0.0033
0.05 0.7555 0.7465 0.0090
0.10 0.7652 0.7526 0.0126
0.30 0.7799 0.7544 0.0255
  • Learning Rate = 0.01 (smallest overfit gap, best generalisation)
  • Learning Rate = 0.05 (Optimal in our case, moderate overfit gap and best validation and test performance)
  • Learning Rate = 0.1 (High training performance but validation and test starts to decline)
  • Learning Rate = 0.3 (Aggressive, highest training AUC but largest overfit gap) - this is a clear indication of overfitting

4.2 Bias-Variance Tradeoff Visualization

This was done for XGBoost to see which estimators perform the best through visualisation, and it was also to establish the bias-variance trade-off, which is how boosting progressively reduces bias while monitoring variance. A basic XGBoost model was built with a learning rate of 0.1 (moderate value) and other parameters from tuning.

The graph was plotted between Boosting Iterations and AUC Score, the key findings from the graph were:

  • Phase 1: Bias Reduction (10-100 estimators)

    • Both training and validation improve rapidly, with AUC improving
    • Gap remains small
    • Dominant effect: Reducing bias by fitting residuals
    • Model learning main patterns

  • Phase 2: Transition (100-250 estimators)

    • Validation improvement slows
    • Training continues to improve
    • Gap widens moderately
    • Approaching optimal complexity at 241 iterations, shown with the red dotted line stopped because of early stopping

  • Phase 3: Variance Dominance (250+ estimators)

    • Validation plateaus and then declines
    • Training keeps improving
    • Gap widens significantly
    • Overfitting: Model memorising training noise

Optimal Point: 241 for this problem Early stopping automatically identifies the optimal bias-variance trade-off point, preventing both underfitting (stopping too early) and overfitting (continuing too long).

Theoretical Connection: This empirically demonstrates the bias-variance decomposition: Expected Test Error = Bias + Variance + Irreducible Error

Early: High Bias, Low Variance Error dominated by bias Optimal: Balanced Bias and Variance Minimum error Late: Low Bias, High Variance Error dominated by variance

Question. Why is the accuracy of XGBoost (scale_pos_weight) low compared to others?

This is because I have used scale_pos_weight here to balance the positive class, which increases recall. But since our dataset is imbalanced, the accuracy doesn't play much of a role; ROC-AUC and PR-AUC matter more to us, and we can clearly see the improvement from Decision Trees to LightGBM. Hence, we will be considering XGBoost without for consistency.

1. Confusion Matrix Analysis

Business Impact Analysis:

For credit default prediction to see why recall is more valuable to us than precision in these cases, we must consider asymmetric costs:

False Negative (FN): Predicts no default, but the customer defaults
Cost: Lost principal + interest (e.g., $10,000 per loan)

Decision Tree FN: 8
XGBoost FN: 43
Savings: loans (83-43) 10,000 = $400,000

False Positive (FP): Predict default, but the customer pays
Cost: Lost interest revenue (e.g., $500 per loan)

Decision Tree FP: 3682
XGBoost FP: 3664
Savings from FP: 18 loans 500 = $9000

Net Benefit: 400,000 + 9000 = $409,000
XGBoosts improved recall (catching more actual defaults) far outweighs the small improvement in false positives, making it strongly preferred from a business perspective.

2. Precision-Recall Curves

Curve Characteristics:

  1. Decision Tree (PR-AUC = 0.1945):
  • Steep initial drop in precision
  • Limited ability to rank predictions
  • Poor discrimination at high recall levels
  1. Gradient Boosting (PR-AUC = 0.2395):
  • Smoother curve, better ranking
  • Maintains reasonable precision up to 50% recall
  • Good improvement over the decision tree
  1. XGBoost (PR-AUC = 0.2477):
  • Dominates other curves at most operating points
  • Superior probability calibration
  1. LightGBM (PR-AUC = 0.2489):
  • Slight edge over XGBoost
  • Best overall discrimination
  • Marginal gains suggest diminishing returns

3.5 XGBoost vs LightGBM

When the time of XGBoost and LightGBM was compared using time, the analysis was done on the notebook. These were our key findings:

  • LightGBM was 1.2X faster than XGBoost.
  • LightGBM tends to train faster, especially on high-dimensional or large datasets.
  • Accuracy is comparable, often slightly better in LightGBM due to the leaf-wise growth strategy.
  • XGBoost uses level-wise growth, which is slightly more conservative but robust.

Question. How do different boosting frameworks handle categorical features and regularisation?

Handling of Categorical Features

Feature XGBoost LightGBM
Categorical Needs one-hot encoding or integer encoding. No native handling. Native support: can accept categorical features directly and find optimal splits.
Performance Can increase dimensionality for many categories Efficient even with high-cardinality categorical features

Regularization:

Aspect XGBoost LightGBM
L1 / L2 regularization Supports reg_alpha (L1) and reg_lambda (L2) Supports lambda_l1, lambda_l2
Tree pruning Depth-based, post-pruning Leaf-wise growth, pre-pruning with num_leaves
Overfitting control max_depth, min_child_weight, gamma num_leaves, min_data_in_leaf, feature_fraction, bagging_fraction

Conclusion:

  • LightGBM can grow deep, asymmetric trees (leaf-wise), which can overfit if not properly regularised.

  • XGBoost grows balanced trees (level-wise), more conservative, sometimes slightly slower, but stable.

4. Discussion and Interpretation

Insights:

  • Ensemble methods (Gradient Boosting, XGBoost, LightGBM) significantly outperformed standalone models.
  • Feature engineering and careful preprocessing (especially imputation + encoding) critically impacted model quality.
  • LightGBM provided the best accuracyspeed trade-off.

Limitations:

  • Hyperparameter tuning was computationally expensive.
  • Model interpretability decreases with complexity (e.g., ensembles vs. Decision Tree).

Conclusion:

The final LightGBM model achieved:

ROC-AUC: 0.76 Average Precision: 0.59 Recall: higher than all baselines

This indicates a reliable and production-ready model for credit default prediction, balancing performance, fairness, and computational efficiency.
